<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-12T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-12T18:00:00-05:00" n="529" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d529">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/10936:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-12T19:00:00-04:00">June 12,
                                    1944—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1479. Reference your 1920, May 29, 5 p.m., and 2003, June 5, noon,<note n="78" xml:id="d529fn1">Latter not printed.</note> Department has
                            not received any confirmation from Stockholm that Johnson and Griffis
                            gave Madame Kollontay assurance quoted in Molotov’s note of May 28.<note n="79" xml:id="d529fn2">See telegram 1920, May 29. 5 p.m., <ref target="#pg_557">p. 557</ref>.</note> As it appears that no
                            general embargo will be placed on the export of ball bearings from
                            Sweden for the time <pb facs="0577" n="567" xml:id="pg_567"/> being the
                            matter is not of immediate importance. However, the Legation at
                            Stockholm has been requested to report regarding their conversation of
                            May 17 with Madame Kollontay and further instructions will then be sent
                            to the Embassy.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>